Ver. 45–47. “Do not think that I will accuse you to the Father; there is one that accuseth
you, even Moses, in whom ye trust. For had ye believed Moses, ye would have believed Me;
for he wrote of Me. But if ye believe not his writings, how shall ye believe My words?”

The Manichæans spring upon these words, saying, “that nothing lies in our own power”;
yet the expression showeth that we are masters of our will. “For if a man cometh to Him,”
saith some one, “what need is there of drawing?” But the words do not take away our free
will, but show that we greatly need assistance. And He implieth not an unwilling1287 comer,
1286 al. “speaking concerning the Jews.”
